<section class="learning-objectives" id="sect-00001">
<title>Learning Outcomes</title>
<para id="para-00001">By the end of this section, you will be able to:</para>
<list id="list-00001">
<item>Identify examples of databases and registries to locate research and evidence-based prevention services.</item>
<item>Identify evidence-based programs that contribute to meeting core public health functions and the 10 Essential Public Health Services.</item>
<item>Understand how to use data to inform decision-making in public health nursing.</item>
</list>
</section>
<para id="para-00002">Once nurses and other health care professionals understand what EBP and EBDM are and when to use these methods, the next steps are to determine where to find <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00001">evidence-based practice interventions</term>. The <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00002">PICOT question</term> is the landmark to use when searching for relevant evidence. This section discusses the different databases and registries nurses may use to find research and information to identify evidence-based prevention services. Additionally, the chapter discusses the <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00003">10 Essential Public Health Services</term>, <term class="no-emphasis" id="term-00004">social determinants of health</term>, and public health functions in consideration of the core public health functions. In addition to databases of literature available to use for research, additional sources of information or guidance include librarians, advanced practice nurses, nursing faculty, nurse educators, risk managers, and professional nursing societies.</para>
<section id="sect-00002">
<title>Databases and Registries</title>
<para id="para-00003">With the vast amount of research available, it is crucial to be efficient while searching for relevant evidence. <term id="term-00005">Databases</term>, collections of information organized in a systematic method, are helpful during the process of searching for sources of existing literature related to the topic of one’s inquiry. Multiple databases are available to assist nurses and other health care providers through the decision-making process of selecting evidence-based interventions. <link target-id="table-00001" document="m00156"/> provides examples of commonly used and reliable databases.</para>
